post_text:
Zech Clemens Named May Student of the Month

Senior Zechariah Clemens received May student of the month. The son of Bill and Denise Clemens, Zech has four siblings: Josh, Ashley, Josie, and Will.

His activities include FCA, FBLA, robotics, basketball and track and field.

His hobbies include hanging out with friends and family, hunting, fishing, watching Netflix, and exercising.

Zech plans to attend Northern State University to major in either athletic training or sports management.

“I can do all things through Christ who strengthens me.” Philippians 4:13.

His role model and inspiration is his grandpa, Cornelius “Connie” Clemens.

His favorite class is business law.

post_text:
Paula Alonso Named April Student of the Month

Foreign-exchange student Paula Alonso received April student of the month. Her host parents are Lisa and Dennis Welch, and her parents are Pelayo and Luisa Alonso. Her siblings include Pelayo and Pablo, who was also an exchange student at Northwestern.

Paula's activities include volleyball and basketball.

Her hobbies include skating, painting, and hanging with friends.

In the future, Paula plans to go to college to be a doctor.

“Live as if you were to die tomorrow. Learn as if you were to live forever.” -- Mahatma Gandhi.

"My favorite athlete is Sofia Bogdanova and my role model is Rafa Nadal," Alonso said.

Her favorite class is art.

Senior Chrissy Stoltenberg received March Student of the Month. Daughter of Jerry and Gail Stoltenberg, Chrissy has two younger siblings: Mack and Dallas.

Her activities include track, volleyball, basketball, FBLA, FFA, FCA and journalism.

Her hobbies include camping and sports.

In the future, Chrissy plans to attend Northern State University to major in accounting and participate in track and field.

Her favorite quote: "Leaders are made, they are not born. They are made by hard effort, which is the price which all of us must pay to achieve any goal that is worthwhile." --Vince Lombardi

post_text:
Mrs. Denise Clemens was recently recognized for being selected as a South Dakota state-level finalist for the Presidential Awards for Excellence in Mathematics and Science Teaching (PAEMST) program.

A high school science teacher at Northwestern, Clemens has been teaching for 25 years.

Before her current position, she taught science at Roncalli Parochial School in Aberdeen.

Clemens earned her bachelor of science in biology, environmental science, and chemistry from Northern State University in 1992 and her bachelor’s degree in 7-12 science and math education also from NSU in 1995.

Clemens has successfully led her students in Science Fair and Science/Quiz Bowl for 23 years. Clemens was a member of the 2015 SD Sci Leadership Cohort, worked with SD EPSCoR, and has participated in many professional workshops and opportunities across South Dakota.
